	<div class="excerpt">
		<p>In this complex world, it’s easy to believe that the future is out of our hands. But there are some who understand that the future doesn’t just happen — it’s made. Among these are the TED Fellows: innovators, activists, artists, inventors and dreamers. The TED Fellows program, now celebrating its fifteenth year, provides communication training, <a class="read-more" title="Read more" href="https://blog.ted.com/meet-the-2024-class-of-ted-fellows/">[<span>&hellip;</span>]</a></p>
	</div>

</article>			
<article id="post-116770" class="post-116770 post type-post status-publish format-standard has-post-thumbnail hentry category-live-from-ted2024 category-news-2 category-ted2024 tag-alex-luebke tag-bilawal-sidhu tag-chris-anderson tag-fei-fei-li tag-helen-toner tag-niceaunties tag-ted tag-ted-conferences tag-ted-talks tag-ted2024 tag-thomas-dohmke tag-vinod-khosla tag-vivek-kumbhari has-thumbnail not-featured even i-12 clearfix" role="article">

			<a href="https://blog.ted.com/mind-expanders-notes-on-session-2-of-ted2024/" data-slug="mind-expanders-notes-on-session-2-of-ted2024" class="post-thumbnail">
			<img src='https://i0.wp.com/blog.ted.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/04/TED2024_20240416_1GT3989-medium.jpg?resize=283%2C212&#038;ssl=1' width='283' height='212' alt='Mind Expanders: Notes on Session 2 of TED2024' />		</a>
		
			<h4>
			<a class="category" href="https://blog.ted.com/category/live-from-ted2024/" data-slug="live-from-ted2024" >
				Live from TED2024			</a>
		</h4>
	
	<h2 class="post-title">
		<a href="https://blog.ted.com/mind-expanders-notes-on-session-2-of-ted2024/" data-slug="mind-expanders-notes-on-session-2-of-ted2024">
			Mind Expanders: Notes on Session 2 of TED2024		</a>
	</h2>

	<div class="meta">
		<div class="meta__author">
			<span>By</span> <a href="https://blog.ted.com/author/claytonwickham/" title="Posts by Clayton Wickham" class="author url fn" rel="author">Clayton Wickham</a>, <a href="https://blog.ted.com/author/crawfordhunt/" title="Posts by Crawford Hunt" class="author url fn" rel="author">Crawford Hunt</a>, <a href="https://blog.ted.com/author/marialadias2/" title="Posts by Maria Ladias" class="author url fn" rel="author">Maria Ladias</a>, <a href="https://blog.ted.com/author/oliverfriedman/" title="Posts by Oliver Friedman" class="author url fn" rel="author">Oliver Friedman</a> and <a href="https://blog.ted.com/author/renaereints22/" title="Posts by Renae Reints" class="author url fn" rel="author">Renae Reints</a>		</div>
		<div class="meta__date">
			<span>on</span>
			<time datetime="2024-04-16" pubdate >
				Apr 16, 2024			</time>
		</div>
	</div>

	<div class="excerpt">
		<p>AI is reshaping how we interact with the world around us and within us, expanding creative possibilities and bringing us closer together by dissolving barriers of all kinds. But anyone who&#8217;s paying attention can spot its obvious flaws and potential pitfalls. From trailblazing platforms making software accessible to micro-robotics revolutionizing health care (including a mind-blowing <a class="read-more" title="Read more" href="https://blog.ted.com/mind-expanders-notes-on-session-2-of-ted2024/">[<span>&hellip;</span>]</a></p>
	</div>

